{  
  "response_text": "The data reveals a sigmoidal trend in the count of households engaging in social learning (household-SL?) over time. Initially, no households exhibit social learning (all columns start at 0 in timestep 0). From timestep 1 onward, social learning begins to accumulate: by timestep 20, total counts range from 8 to 15 across columns (e.g., column 19 reaches 15 at timestep 20, while column 29 reaches 47). By timestep 50, counts per column generally stabilize, with most values ranging between 24–38 households. At timestep 100, all columns plateau at values between 35 and 50 households, with the highest values (e.g., column 29 at 54) occurring earlier in the simulation. A sharp inflection point occurs between timesteps 38 and 50, where counts per column increase by 12–15 households on average, after which growth slows. This pattern suggests an activation of social learning mechanisms (E-RO-SL1 agents) within the population, constrained by the knowledge-radius parameter (1.0) limiting information diffusion to immediate neighbors. The late-time plateau aligns with the resting?=False parameter, as no global strategy shifts (**SL2-strategy-switch? = False**) prevent community-wide saturation. The variability between columns reflects overlapping confidence intervals or stochasticity in agent-level adoptions, but all behavioral types (E-RO, E-LBD, E-RO-SL1) converge to similar equilibrium levels by timestep 100 due to homogeneous initial conditions (**homog-behav-types? = True**). Risk sensitivity (**risk-mode? = True**) and climate shocks (**global-rain? = True**) likely modulate the tempo of adoption but do not alter the asymptotic outcome."  
}

